Lab 3: Install an Operator using the CLI

Objective
Install an Operator using OperatorGroup and Subscription.

Step 1: Create a project
oc new-project operator-demo

Step 2: Create the OperatorGroup
Create operatorgroup.yaml

apiVersion: operators.coreos.com/v1
kind: OperatorGroup
metadata:
  name: operator-demo-group
  namespace: operator-demo
spec:
  targetNamespaces:
  - operator-demo

Apply it:
oc apply -f operatorgroup.yaml

Step 3: Identify the exact operator package name

Check available package manifests:
oc get packagemanifest -n openshift-marketplace | head

Search for a package:
oc get packagemanifest -n openshift-marketplace | grep -i node

You can also inspect one:
oc describe packagemanifest <package-name> -n openshift-marketplace

Step 4: Create the Subscription
Example subscription.yaml:

apiVersion: operators.coreos.com/v1alpha1
kind: Subscription
metadata:
  name: nfd
  namespace: operator-demo
spec:
  channel: stable
  name: nfd
  source: redhat-operators
  sourceNamespace: openshift-marketplace
  installPlanApproval: Automatic

Apply it:
oc apply -f subscription.yaml
Note: if nfd is not the exact package name in your cluster, replace it with the package name from packagemanifest.

Step 5: Verify installation
oc get subscription -n operator-demo
oc get installplan -n operator-demo
oc get csv -n operator-demo
oc get pods -n operator-demo

Troubleshooting
If CSV does not become Succeeded, check:
oc describe subscription nfd -n operator-demo
oc describe csv -n operator-demo
oc get events -n operator-demo


Quick CLI diagram
    Namespace
       ↓
    OperatorGroup
       ↓
    Subscription
       ↓
    InstallPlan
       ↓
    CSV Succeeded

