Lab 5: Control application permissions with SCC

Objective
Understand Security Context Constraints and how OpenShift restricts containers.

What will be covered:
Why pods fail under default SCC
How to inspect SCCs
How to grant an SCC to a service account

Step 1: View SCCs
oc get scc

Step 2: Inspect the default restricted SCC
oc describe scc restricted-v2
If your cluster uses a different name, check restricted.

This SCC prevents many risky behaviors:
running as root
privileged mode
host networking
hostPath access

Step 3: Create a pod that may require elevated permissions

Create root-pod.yaml

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: root-test
spec:
  containers:
  - name: root-test
    image: nginx


Apply it:
oc apply -f root-pod.yaml

Step 4: Check why it fails
oc get pod root-test
oc describe pod root-test

Expected
You should see an SCC-related denial.

Step 5: Grant a less restrictive SCC
oc adm policy add-scc-to-user anyuid -z default -n student-n1

This grants the anyuid SCC to the default service account in the current namespace.

Step 6: Delete and recreate the pod
oc delete pod root-test
oc apply -f root-pod.yaml
oc get pod root-test
Now it should start.

Arch diagram
    Pod requests settings
          ↓
    OpenShift checks SCC
          ↓
    Allowed? → Pod runs
    Denied?  → Pod blocked

