Lab 6: Allow application access to Kubernetes APIs
Objective

Allow a pod to query the Kubernetes API using a service account and RBAC.

Step 1: Create a project
oc new-project api-access-demo

Step 2: Create a service account
oc create serviceaccount api-reader

Step 3: Create a Role
Create role.yaml

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: Role
metadata:
  name: pod-reader
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
  resources: ["pods"]
  verbs: ["get", "list"]

Apply it:
oc apply -f role.yaml

Step 4: Bind the role to the service account
oc create rolebinding api-reader-binding \
  --role=pod-reader \
  --serviceaccount=api-access-demo:api-reader

Step 5: Run a pod using that service account
oc run api-test \
  --image=registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9/ubi-minimal \
  --serviceaccount=api-reader \
  --command -- sleep 3600

Step 6: Open a shell
oc rsh pod/api-test
Inside the pod, test token and API access:

TOKEN=$(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token)
CACERT=/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/ca.crt
NAMESPACE=$(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/namespace)
curl -s --cacert $CACERT -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
https://kubernetes.default.svc/api/v1/namespaces/$NAMESPACE/pods

Expected result
You should get JSON output listing pods in that namespace.

This is how applications safely access the Kubernetes API:
ServiceAccount identity
RBAC permissions
mounted token/cert

